metadata.description:
Addendum to Annuls of WorSAGE (the Worshipful Society of Adventurers and Generative Explorers) XXVII.Vol.2048

There is a significantly common phenomena in which Pairs of "Tails of Majestic Creatures" are found together. Various sketches of these "Pairs" have been collated and are available, free of charge, the collectors of the initial Tails of Majestic Creatures collection based upon a recently taken collection registry snapshot. 

These sketches are available on a one per collector basis and for a limited time only after which they will no longer be accessible.

The sketches come in 2 forms - an ink and color style, and a pencil style - for which different colored paper has been used.

The digitally minded can press s to get a 5000x3000 download of a sketch.

objkt.name: KINJO! #173

metadata.name: KINJO! #173
metadata.description:
A celebration of my 1 year in the Tezos art space, KINJO is an experiment in pure abstraction and randomness. With a simple grid at its core, this piece attempts to play with lively colors, completely unique variations, and host the nice surprises that randomness can bring.

My intention when starting to work in the Tezos space was to play with the surrender of control in art, that idea had always fascinated me. In the beginning it was working with GAN, digitally painting a piece or processing my own photography, and sending it through my own frankensteined colab notebook. I was creating something and then trusting a process to rip it apart and create something new. I moved on to the Ganerations project, which was essentially gen art in layered pngs and processed through my GAN notebook. I found generative art and fxHash shortly after and have been incredibly thankful for the community here, as well as inspired every day by the new approaches I see from both new and established artists on the platform. I'm learning every day.

Gen art is the perfect place for me to express myself and explore the themes of control and trust with my work, and I thank you all for following along and supporting my work :)

issuer.name: KINJO!

objkt.name: SETNAS #1

metadata.name: SETNAS #1
metadata.description:
SETNAS

-NOTES:

-100% code generated (no images or sounds preloaded)

-'Click' to START/pause.

-Save current frame to PNG-> press 'S' or  drag on top of screen.

-Save 2 s. animation to GIF-> press 'G' or drag on bottom of screen.

-All audio stuff is done with WebPd.

-All visual is done with p5js.

-Chrome browser recommended

-Headphones recomended. Some extreme sounds (frequency and amplitude) can be generated.

-Supply can be halved/reduced and/or the price can be doubled if all iterations have not been minted (every 24h aprox).

DESCRIPTION:

-An audiovisual piece based on randomly generated patterns. These patterns generate endless unique pieces of electronic music (and their corresponding visuals).

-This is a 16-step sequencer based on 2 basic patterns: the kick drum and the tuplets of each kick.

-In each cycle (from 16 to 64 kicks) there can be changes to many of the parameters of the patterns, thus generating changes to the piece in an infinite way.

FEATURES:

-"tipusGrid": type of grid-> (lines, rects, soroll (noise), ASCII, mosaic or barcode).
-"baseShape": first cicle base shape (rect, circle,lines, vlines or hlines).
-"baseSize": size of base shape.
-"gridDensity": grid size (16, 32 or 64).
-"alpha": alpha of base image.
-"alpha2": alpha of canvas.
-"darkMode": dark mode (true) or light mode (false).
-"color": color of lines (dark mode) or background (light mode)-> white, red, green or blue.
-"bpm": Beats Per Minute. from 90 to 160 -> this value is theoretical, some devices may not be able to play the piece at a certain speed.
-"tipusBass": type of bass drum (from 0 to 5).
-"maxTuplet": max number of tuplets for each kick.
-"reverb": has reverb effect (audio)

issuer.name: SETNAS

objkt.name: Richter #180

metadata.name: Richter #180
metadata.description:
Richter is the second collaboration of Richard Nadler and Leander Herzog, following their first project called Gerhard. A generative animation based on multiple layers of color and data, mixed, moved and painted over in realtime. Some fragments stick to the canvas while others get discarded to leave the existing layers visible, allowing a complex surface to emerge and build up over time.
 
Richter works with data from 4 of 24 highres images, 30mb in total. This is the maximum size fxhash allows for a project and three times more than Gerhard. Richard Nadler created stunning new textures, enabling more variation in composition and detail to emerge at much higher resolution. Leander Herzog created the code for the interplay between the layers, motion and interactions. Richter elevates the approach from Gerhard with new methods for the realtime rendering process and new features like offline-first caching. Both artists use different tools and are not aware of the details of each others process, meeting through the interface of pixels as data.
 
Richter is featured in the exhibition "Generative Abstraction" at Expanded.art in Berlin.
 
- Click to start a new layer of motion and color.
- Doubleclick to enter fullscreen.
- Press “s” to save the canvas.
- Append ?dpr=4 to the url to increase the resolution.

leanderherzog.ch/2023/richter/
leanderherzog.ch/2022/gerhard/
fxhash.xyz/generative/17030/

issuer.name: Richter
